<h2>How to Evaluate a Fulfillment Partner's SLA</h2>

<p>When reviewing a fulfillment provider's proposed SLA, ask these specific questions:</p>

<ol>
<li><strong>Are the metrics defined precisely?</strong> Vague commitments like "fast processing" or "high accuracy" are meaningless. Every metric should have a number attached.</li>
<li><strong>How is performance measured and reported?</strong> You should receive automated monthly (or weekly) reports showing actual performance against each SLA target. If they measure manually, the data is unreliable.</li>
<li><strong>What are the exclusions?</strong> Every SLA has exceptions (force majeure, your own data errors, carrier delays). Make sure the exclusion list is reasonable and not so broad that it negates the agreement.</li>
<li><strong>What are the penalties?</strong> If there are no consequences for missing targets, the SLA is decorative. Insist on service credits, per-incident compensation, or both.</li>
<li><strong>Is there a review mechanism?</strong> SLAs should be reviewed and updated at least annually to reflect changes in your business, volume, and market expectations.</li>
</ol>

<h2>MTP Group's SLA Commitments</h2>

<p>At MTP Group, we believe transparency builds trust. Here is what our standard SLA includes for all fulfillment clients:</p>

<ul>
<li>99.7% order accuracy guarantee with per-incident compensation for errors.</li>
<li>Same-day dispatch for all orders received before 14:00, seven days a week.</li>
<li>Real-time inventory dashboard with 99%+ accuracy verified by weekly cycle counts.</li>
<li>24-hour returns processing with automated status updates to your system.</li>
<li>Dedicated account manager with 1-hour response time during business hours.</li>
<li>Monthly performance reports with full breakdown by SLA metric.</li>
</ul>

<p>We include penalty clauses in every contract because we are confident in our operations. When you set a high bar and measure against it daily, you rarely fall short. And when you do, owning the failure and compensating the client is the only way to maintain a relationship built on trust.</p>

<h2>Building a Culture of Accountability</h2>

<p>An SLA is only as strong as the operational discipline behind it. The best logistics partners do not treat SLAs as a compliance exercise. They embed them into daily operations: real-time dashboards on the warehouse floor, daily team huddles around KPIs, and root cause analysis for every exception. If your fulfillment partner cannot articulate their process for continuous improvement, their SLA commitments are fragile at best.</p>

<p>For e-commerce owners, the takeaway is simple: demand an SLA, read it carefully, ensure it has teeth, and hold your partners accountable. It is the single most effective tool for ensuring your logistics operation performs at the level your customers expect.</p>

