<section class="faq-section">
<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q">What does SLA stand for in logistics?</div>
<div class="faq-a">SLA stands for Service Level Agreement. In logistics and fulfillment, it is a formal contract between a business and its logistics partner that defines measurable performance standards such as order accuracy rates, processing times, shipping deadlines, and response times for issue resolution. A strong SLA also includes penalty clauses for non-compliance.</div>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q">What are the most important SLA metrics for e-commerce fulfillment?</div>
<div class="faq-a">The five most critical SLA metrics are: order accuracy rate (target 99.5%+), same-day processing rate (target 98%+), inventory accuracy (target 99%+), damage rate (target under 0.5%), and issue resolution time (target under 4 hours). These KPIs directly impact customer satisfaction, return rates, and overall profitability.</div>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q">What happens if a fulfillment provider breaks their SLA?</div>
<div class="faq-a">A well-structured SLA includes penalty clauses for non-compliance. Common penalties include service credits (5-15% discount on monthly fees), financial compensation for specific errors (e.g., per-order penalty for mis-ships), and escalation procedures. The contract should also define conditions for early termination if SLA breaches become systematic over a defined period.</div>
</div>
</section>


